==English==
===Etymology===
Old English ''[[cribb]]'', '[[manger]]', '[[stall]]'. The overall sense seems to be that of a boxy, wooden structure, often of rough construction. The sense of stealing, 'taking notes, 'plagiarize'' seems to have developed out of the verb.
===Pronunciation===
*krĭb, /krɪb/, /<tt>krIb</tt>/
*:[[Rhymes:English:-ɪb|Rhymes: -ɪb]]

===Noun===
[[Category:English nouns]]
{{en-noun}}
# A baby's [[bed]] (British [[cot]]) with [[high]], often [[slatted]], often moveable [[side]]s, suitable for a child who has outgrown a [[cradle]] or [[bassinet]].
# A [[manger]], a feeding [[trough]] for [[animal]]s.
#:{{RQ:AV}}''And she brought forth her firstborn son, and wrapped him in swaddling clothes, and laid him in a manger; because there was no room for them in the inn.'' — Luke 2:7 
# A [[bin]] for drying or storing [[grain]], as with a [[corn crib]].
# A [[stall]] for large domestic animals.
#:{{RQ:AV}}''Where no oxen are, the crib is clean: but much increase is by the strength of the ox.'' — Proverbs 14:4 [[KJV]]
# {{rare}} A [[creche]] or [[Nativity]] [[scene]] consisting of [[statue]]s of [[Mary]], [[Joseph]] and [[Jesus]], and various other characters such as the [[magi]], but with particular reference to the baby Jesus in the [[manger]].
# A boxy structure traditionally built of heavy wooden [[timber]]s, to support an existing structure from below, as with a [[mineshaft]] or a building being raised off its foundation in preparation for being moved; see [[cribbing]].
# A small freestanding [[shack]]; a [[hovel]].
#:''How many thousand of my poorest subjects
#:''Are at this hour asleep! O sleep, O gentle sleep,
#:''Nature's soft nurse, how have I frighted thee,
#:''That thou no more wilt weigh my eyelids down
#:''And steep my senses in forgetfulness?
#:''Why rather, sleep, liest thou in smoky '''cribs''',
#:''Upon uneasy pallets stretching thee
#:''And hush'd with buzzing night-flies to thy slumber,
#:''Than in the perfumed chambers of the great,
#:''Under the canopies of costly state,
#:''And lull'd with sound of sweetest melody?'' — Shakespeare, ''Henry IV Part 2'', Act 3, Scene 1
# A small room, especially one of rough construction.
# A shack or roughly finished room used for prostitution.
#:''The lowest form of Old West prostitutes worked out of ad hoc cribs.''
# {{slang}} One's residence, or where one normally hangs out.
# {{rare}} ''(built on the verb-sense)'' A minor theft, as with intellectual property, e.g., [[plagiarism]].
#:''A lot of Wiktionary entries look like cribs from dictionaries still under copyright.''
# ''(usually plural)'' A collection of quotes or references for use in speaking or or for assembling a written document; a [[crib sheet]].
#:''These cribs are taken from a Google on "foobar".''
# {{cattag|Cribbage}}: Short for the [[card game]] [[cribbage]].
# {{cattag|Cribbage}}: The cards [[discard]]ed by [[player]]s and used by the [[dealer]].
# (''[[cryptanalysis]]'') A known piece of [[information]] [[corresponding]] to a section of [[encrypted]] text, that is then used to work out the remaining sections.<!--This is not an example of the usage of the word:
Eg, during [[WW2]], British [[cryptanalysts]] knew that many [[German]] messages contained the term "Heil Hitler", and were able to use this [[pattern]] to help work out the day's [[encryption]] codes.-->

